The '''Cosmic Hunt''' is an old and widely distributed family of cognate myths. They are stories about a large animal that is pursued by hunters, is wounded, and is transformed into a [[constellation]]. Variants of the Cosmic Hunt are common in cultures of Northern Eurasia and the Americas, and include the story of [[Callisto (mythology)|Callisto]] in classical sources.<ref name="SciAm"/> The prey animal is either a [[bear]] or an [[ungulate]], and the constellation it is transformed into is typically the four stars of the bowl in the [[Big Dipper]] [[Asterism (astronomy)|asterism]] of [[Ursa Major]]. In some variants blood or grease may fall from the wounded animal, in an [[Iroquois]] version the blood causes leaves to change color in autumn.<ref name="SciAm">{{cite news|last1=d'Huy|first1=Julien|title=Scientists Trace Society’s Myths to Primordial Origins|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/scientists-trace-society-rsquo-s-myths-to-primordial-origins/|accessdate=15 December 2016|issue=December|publisher=[[Scientific American]]|date=2016}}</ref> Sometimes the hunters are also placed in the firmament, represented by the stars of the Big Dipper's handle.

The original prototype of the myth must have been invented at least 15,000 years ago for it to have diffused across the [[Beringia|Bering land bridge]].<ref name="d'Huy 2013">{{cite journal|last1=d'Huy|first1=Julien|title=A Cosmic Hunt in the Berber sky: : a phylogenetic reconstruction of a Palaeolithic mythology|journal=Les Cahiers de l'AARS|date=2013|volume=16|pages=93–106|url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00932197/document|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>

